including an RJ45 jack and transformers. It can also accelerate some
This board connects readily available IDE storage devices (40-pin,
parallel) to the computer. IDE devices are very easy to interface
to the CFT they require little more than address decoding.
This card provides one or two 82C54 programmable timers, and a
combination Real Time Clock and 2 kByte (note: not kWord) Non-
Volatile RAM where settings and bootstrap code may be stored.
Perhaps surprisingly for a hardware project, there's a lot of code in a
number of languages, mainly C, Python, CFT Assembly and Verilog.

Multiplexes external interrupts and allows them to be individually
masked and responded to by the CPU. Drives front panel display to
show interrupts enabled and interrupt requests.
Minis generally communicate with the user via serial terminals. This
board provides two or four of them with provision for DTE, DCE or TTL.
TTL (non-RS232) is used to connect to FTDI serial-to-USB bridges.
This card is still being designed. It would output an analogue VGA-
compatible display signal with a native resolution of 640480 and
64 colours. Horizontal pixel clocks can generate 320 or 640 pixels per
raster, allowing for 40 or 80 column text. Low resolution graphics
use full (multi-colour) or half (semi-graphic) text cells for 40, 80 or
160 PELs per row. The vertical clock can generate 25, 50, 100, 200 or
400 lines. 25 and 50 are used for text. Features: single or double
buffer; separate colour & bitmap planes; horizontal and vertical
resolution independently selectable; hardware scroll; hardware
One to three 16-bit banks of memory on a board. One bank is ROM,
the other two are RAM. Each bank accommodates 512 kWords of
memory. The card takes up of the CFT's total address space.
The keyboard card attaches a PS/2 style keyboard to the CFT. Plans to
use simpler (parallel) keyboards failed because old keyboards are not
easy to find. More advanced keyboards like Sun (TTL serial) could be
considered, including a hardware-assisted key matrix scanner which
saves the computer the need to keep scanning the keyboard.
The sound card implements a General Instrument AY-3-8910 PSG
device and/or a SpeakJet speech synthesizer. Sound is amplified on-
board in stereo and is also output via a standard 3.5mm TRS jack.
The Programmer's Front Panel (PFP) is the traditional way to operate
a mini. It's also a very good way to diagnose and debug issues with
software, hardware and even microcode. The PFP consists of a light
board (LEDs), a switch board, and a controller board. Support for it
The processor is built on 3 interconnected 6U (2316 cm) cards. It's
a microcoded accumulator machine similar to the DEC PDP-8, with a
less orthogonal but more capable instruction set (IS). All instructions
are exactly 16 bits and the IS is easily expanded. Minor operations
are like the PDP-8's microcoded instructions: one instruction can
perform a combination of up to 10 different operations. There are
24 of these instructions, so the IS can be said to have between 16
and 4,110 instructions. Future extensions to the microcode are
possible such that more powerful, multi-word instructions can be
implemented with almost no changes in hardware.

flowRoot.flowPara: This poster shows the current status of the CFT Project, including some statistics. The CFT Project is a long-term project to create a computer from scratch, using parts you could have bought off the shelf in the Seventies and Eighties: 74xxx chips and a few LSI components. Everything, including the processor, is designed and built from scratch. This includes many of the software and hardware tools. A few modern components were used. (larger memory chips, for instance it's difficult and expensive to find small devices nowadays, and why bother?) Initially, the computer will look like a Sixties mini: processor, memory, serial ports and full control panel. As construction progresses, the machine will start getting more modern features, culminating in a system with IDE hard disks (no floppies unless I can find a floppy controller chip), keyboard and video support, and even Ethernet.

The processor's microcode, instruction set and all software is homebrew, and most of the tools I didn't make myself are Freeware, Open Source, Software Libre, call it what you will. The only non-free piece of software is the electronics CAD used to draw the schematics. Python, GNU C, Inkscape, XeLaTeX, Linux, KDE, the GIMP, Digikam and GNU Emacs are a few among the dozens of programs leveraged to get from the early conceptual notes to more than a dozen of Eurocards radiating heat like there's no tomorrow. The CFT Project is developed in my Copious Free Time (sarcastically). Whenever there's progress, I tend to document it on the BedroomLAN site, Twitter and Flickr, with occasional updates of a thoroughly obscure Facebook page.
